  "text": "The term 'permeability' is used to describe the passive penetration of the intestinal barrier by non-charged and usually non-absorbable macromolecules [CITATION_1] ). An increase in the permeability of the intestinal wall to macromolecules in comparison to normal intestine is thought to result from migration through the junctional complex (paracellular route), through ulcerations or across extrusion zones at the villous tip. The degree of intestinal permeability is usually assessed by measuring the urinary excretion of orally administered non-metabolized macromolecules such as sugars (lactulose, mannitol, rhamnose, cellobiose), inert polymers (polyethylene glycol, FITC-dextran) or radiolabelled compounds ([\"CrIEDTA, [89mT~]diethylenetriaminepenta-acetic acid (DTPA); [CITATION_2] .",
